'''John Owen Hughes''' (d. February 1945) was a British businessman in Hong Kong and member of the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]] and [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].

==Career==
J. Owen Hughes was a well-known British expatriate in Hong Kong in the colonial period. He was the head of the Harry Wicking & Co.<ref name="elected">{{cite news|newspaper=Hong Kong Daily Press|date=17 May 1931|page=7|title=Legislative Council Nominee}}</ref> He was also appointed member of the board of the [[Union Insurance Society of Canton]] in 1927.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=1 June 1927|page=8|title=Untitled}}</ref> He joined the [[Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce]] and became an active member in the Chamber. He served on the committee of the Chamber from 1921 to 1931 and in 1924 he was elected the Chairman of the Chamber in succession to [[Dallas Gerald Mercer Bernard|D. G. M. Bernard]]. He had also been Chairman of the Metals Sub-Committee for years.<ref name="resigned">{{cite news|newspaper=Hong Kong Daily Press|date=5 May 1931|page=7|title=Mr. C. G. S. Mackie}}</ref>

Owen Hughes was the representative of the Chamber on the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]] from 1927 to 1931.<ref name="resigned"/> He was elected in May 1927 to take place from the chairman of the Chamber D. G. M. Bernard as the representative of the Chamber.<ref name="elected"/> He resigned from the committee and the representation of the Chamber of Commerce on the Legislative Council from 25 April 1931.<ref name="resigned"/> He was again appointed to the Legislative Council temporarily in May 1934 during [[Henry Pollock]] on leave.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Hongkong Government|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|date=10 May 1934|number=374}}</ref>

He was appointed to the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]] on several occasions, in May and October 1928 and in July 1930 for Henry Pollock.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Hongkong Government|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|date=8 May 1928|number=264}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=The Hongkong Government|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|date=2 October 1928|number=545}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=The Hongkong Government|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|date=18 July 1930|number=440}}</ref>

Among others he was also member of the Licensing Board and the Authorized Architects' Committee.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Hongkong Government|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|date=16 March 1925|number=155}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=The Hongkong Government|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|date=15 October 1927|number=602}}</ref>

During his stay in Hong Kong, Owen Hughes joined the Victoria Lodge of the [[Freemasonry]] and became the Master. In August 1926, appointed the District Grand Master of English Freemasonry for Hong Kong and South China, in succession to [[Percy Hobson Holyoak|P. H. Hoyoak]] who deceased.<ref name="freemason">{{cite news|newspaper=Hong Kong Daily Press|date=30 August 1926|page=5|title=Hongkong and South China Freemasons}}</ref>

==Death and family==
He was held as prisoner of war at the [[Stanley Internment Camp]] during the [[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]] and died in February 1945

John Owen Hughes' son Harry Owen Hughes was a well-known [[cricketer]] in Hong Kong. He was married to Frances Isabel Oakley, daughter of H. G. Oakley of [[Berkhamsted]], [[Hertfordshire]]. The wedding took place at [[St. John's Cathedral, Hong Kong]] on 7 December 1929 and was attended by Governor [[Cecil Clementi]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Singapore Free Press and Mercantile Advertiser|date=20 December 1929|page=12|title=Popular Hong Kong Cricketer Weds}}</ref>

