'''Thaung Su Nyein''' ({{lang-my|သောင်းစုငြိမ်း}}; born 1977<ref name="roughneen">{{cite news|url=http://www.irrawaddy.org/business/economy/for-burmas-new-newspapers-a-daily-struggle-to-profit.html|title=For Burma’s New Newspapers, a Daily Struggle to Profit|last=Roughneen|first=Simon|date=26 August 2013|work=The Irrawaddy|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>) is a Burmese businessman. He founded Information Matrix, a media company, which publishes [[7Day News|7Day Daily]], one of Myanmar's highest circulated news journals.<ref name="bbc">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-23901922|title=My Business: Running a newspaper in Burma|date=4 September 2013|work=BBC|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> He is the son of [[Win Aung (minister)|Win Aung]], a former Burmese foreign minister.<ref name="bbc"/> He served as 7Day's editor-in-chief.<ref name="khm">{{cite news|url=http://www.mmtimes.com/index.php/home-page/142-feature/1511-myanmar-media-reform-publish-and-be-damned.html|title=Myanmar media reform: Publish and be damned?|last=Kyaw Hsu Mon |author2=Nan Tin Htwe |date=7 January 2013|work=Myanmar Times|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> He studied [[computer science]] at [[City College of New York]] but exited after his 3rd year to return to Myanmar.<ref name="mbc">{{cite web|url=http://www.myanmarbizconference.com/thaung-su-nyein/|title=U Thaung Su Nyein|work=Myanmar Business Conference |accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>
He is married to Su Su Soe Nyunt and has 2 sons.<ref name="mbc"/>
